      <h4>Avoid/escape was the consequence in 81% of all task demands</h4>
      <p>Of 36 total task demands across 10 days, 29 resulted in TB#1 being triggered — meaning JJ successfully avoided initiating the task. In the majority of those, the task was either removed or adult support stepped in to complete it for him, reinforcing the avoidance pattern.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="finding coral">
      <h4>Only 7 of 36 demands met the independence criterion</h4>
      <p>Independent initiation — latency under 2 minutes with zero adult prompts — occurred on only 7 task demands across the full 10-day period. All 7 were concentrated in Apr 17 (3 demands) and Apr 20 (3 demands), with 1 on Apr 21. All Resource Room sessions with active Seeker proximity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div>
    <div class="finding amber">
      <h4>NI events cluster in Library and Gen Ed settings</h4>
      <p>All 6 no-initiation events — where the task demand ended with zero independent initiation — occurred on Apr 6 (1), Apr 13 (2), Apr 14 (1), and Apr 15 (2). Apr 14 and Apr 15 are Library/Gen Ed sessions. This confirms the setting-specific nature of the most severe expression of TB#1.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="finding green">
      <h4>Apr 14 — zero TB#2 despite 1 TB#1 NI event</h4>
      <p>The only day with zero TB#2 occurrences still had a TB#1 NI event, confirming that passive avoidance substituted for physical escape on that day. The ABC consequence was still escape — just achieved through non-initiation rather than seat departure. The function remained identical.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="bip">
  <div class="lbl">What the ABC task data confirm</div>
  <p>Across all 10 days and all 36 task demands, the antecedent was consistently an independent reading or writing demand, the behavior was consistently non-initiation (TB#1) and/or seat departure (TB#2), and the consequence was consistently escape or avoidance of the demand — confirmed in 29 of 36 demands (81%). The 7 independent initiations — all in structured RR sessions with Seeker proximity — confirm the behavior is not a skill deficit but a performance deficit maintained by negative reinforcement. This is the strongest evidence base for an escape/avoidance function across the full observation period.</p>
